@berrycar Rate in rest of US is double. Not meant to scare. If your daughter is a risk make sure you and She advocates for her health with her OB when time comes ((Hugs))

@berrycar In my hospital we put them on prophylactic lovenox usually. Yes incision hematoma is a risk for c-sections but you can get transfused with more blood. You can die instantaneously from a PE. I love hospitals in Cali. Rate of maternal death here is comparable to Canada/Australia..

@BookThingo @slamup Very very sad. Id say even with the differences between your birth experience and the one in my hospital for example, I would vouch your top notch care in a hospital in Cali, but couldnt say same outside of the state. Which shouldnt be the case.

@slamup @BookThingo Im just gonna throw this in for kicks bc I have no audience on twitter or even my personal FB account. US maternal death rate is higher than many other developed countries! However Im proud to say Californias is much lower, and closer to Australia and Canadas rate.

@slamup @BookThingo So with an epidural it doesnt take away the feeling of pressure. Without epidurals that breathing pattern is still used. With epidurals we tell patients to hold their breath and push for 10 seconds. Like theyre pooping
@BookThingo @slamup Well we figured it out. All comes down to $$. We wont even talk about the rate of c-sections here in the US. Lol

@BookThingo @slamup Yes for sure. Its the insurance system. Australian taxes pay for their care I suppose? And no matter what kind of care they get, the hospital wont get paid more. And it cost them $ to induce, give IVs, use epidurals, pay a Doctor etc

@slamup @BookThingo I think it stems from insurance. The more interventions imposed the more the hospital and OBs get paid. Inducing labor, IV, epidurals, meds, all cost $$. The cost to patient is same mind you bc of copays being a set number. But the hospital/OBs can charge insurance for all those.
@BookThingo @slamup Thats crazy to me! Its so different! Moms here are always on IV. It gets started on admission. They wouldnt get dehydrated at all.

Damn. The hospital and her OB of all ppl shouldve known her history of pulmonary embolism. And shouldve had her on prophylactic anticoagulant. All hospitals and care are really and truly not equal.http://www.skepticalob.com/2018/01/serena-williams-almost-becomes-a-maternal-mortality-statistic.html

@slamup @BookThingo Yes it stuck with me, bc of the difference between births in Australia and here. Doulas are BYO here as well. No midwives (except nurse midwives but they are rare) have ANY hospital privileges here. They are seen as hacks by OBs.

@slamup @BookThingo Hahah good point on epidurals and pain. Unfortunately bc epidurals are widely used, that position is just what OBs and nurses are used to. Its the default position even if theres no epidurals.

@slamup @BookThingo I think Ive read your account Kat, of midwives attending births? And doulas presence? Midwife and doula attended births arent the norm here at all. And unfortunately the midwives here arent as educated/regulated as those from other countries. With nurse midwives as exception.

@slamup @BookThingo Oh so thats the other thing, epidurals are used here in the majority of deliveries. Thats why the positions so prevalent. Even in births Ive attended with no epidurals, its still the position used. Some womens hospital and some OBs try other positions. Its a rarity tho.
@BookThingo @slamup Its sadly how its done in the US still. Theyre slightly elevated but yea essentially (Im an OB nurse).
